<Header Files>
#include <iostream>     input and output stream header file
#include <string>       string methods and functions

<Arithmetic operators>
+   Addition
-   Substraction 
/   Division
*   Multiplication
%   Modulus
++  Incrementation
--  Decrementation

<Assigment Operators>
=   Setting value                       x = 5
+=  Adding to the set value             x = x + 3
-=  Susbtracting to the set value       x = x - 3
*=  Multipying the set value            x = x * 3
/=  Dividing the set value              x = x / 3
%=  Moduling the set operator           x = x % 3
^=  The set exponent operator           x = x ^ 3
&=  bitwise AND assignment operator     x = x & 3 
          ________________________
          |     5 -> binary: 101 |  --> It compares like 1 0 1
          |     3 -> binary: 011 |                       0 1 1
          | 5 & 3 ->         001 |                       = = =
          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯                       0 0 1
|=  bitwise OR assignment operator      x = x | 3
          ________________________
          |     5 -> binary: 101 |  --> It compares like 1 0 1
          |     3 -> binary: 011 |                       0 1 1
          | 5 | 3 ->         001 |                       = = =
          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯                       1 1 1 = 7         
>>= right-shift assignment operator     x = x >> 3
          _____________________________
          | 16 -> 10000               |            
          | 16 >>= 2 = 00100          |                
          |         ~> 12       100=4 |                           
          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯ 
<<= Right-shift assigment operator      x = x << 3      
          _____________________________
          | 4 -> 00100                |            
          | 4 <<= 2 = 10000           |                
          |        ~> 21    10000=16  |                           
          ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯ 

<Comparison Operators>
==	    Equal to	                x == y	
!=	    Not equal	                x != y	
>	    Greater than	            x > y	
<	    Less than	                x < y	
>=	    Greater than or equal to	x >= y	
<=	    Less than or equal to	    x <= y

<Logical Operators>
&& 	Logical and	Returns true if both statements are true	                x < 5 && x < 10	
|| 	Logical or	Returns true if one of the statements is true	            x < 5 || x < 4	
!	Logical not	Reverse the result, returns false if the result is true	   !(x < 5 && x < 10)

<Precedence of Operators>
1-  ()          Parentheses
2-  * / %       Multiplication, Division, Modulus
3-  + -         Addition and Subtraction
4-  > < >= <=   Comparison
5-  == !=       Equality
6-  &&          Logical AND
7-  ||          Logical OR
8-  =           Assignment

<formating Operators>
\n         new line 
std::endl  new line
\t         horizontal tab
\\         inserts \
\"         inserts "
    
<program flow>
int main() { }      main loop (case sensetive)

<Variable Types>
Note: You can use sizeof(var) for looking at the size of somethin

int             entire numbers                  2 or 4 bytes
double          comma numbers 15 dec digits     8 bytes
float           comma numbers 6-7 dec digits    4 bytes

char            single characters               1 byte
std::string     text                            1 byte per letter       <needs strings library>
bool            True or False                   1 byte


<Variable Modifiers>
const           makes variable read only

<Scope and Extractors>
std     standard library
::      scope parameters
<<      insertion paramenters
>>      extraction paramenters
//      comment
/**/    multiple line comment

<commands>
std::cout << "Hello, World";       print on terminal command
std::cin >> x;

<KeyWords>
auto    makes the compiler figure out the type of variable you want to put

